  mark stable on amd64

*speex-1.0.2 (21 Nov 2003)

  21 Nov 2003; Martin Holzer <mholzer@gentoo.org> speex-1.0.2.ebuild:
  Version bumped.

  09 Nov 2003; Jason Wever <weeve@gentoo.org> speex-1.0.ebuild:
  Marked stable on sparc.

  17 Oct 2003; Nick Hadaway <raker@gentoo.org> speex-1.0.1.ebuild:
  Added the missing ${myconf} required to specify oggvorbis and sse 
  support.

  04 Oct 2003; Brad House <brad_mssw@gentoo.org> speex-1.0.ebuild:
  add ~amd64 flag

  02 Jul 2003; Nick Hadaway <raker@gentoo.org> speex-1.0.1.ebuild:
  Added oggvorbis and sse use variable support.

*speex-1.0.1 (21 Jun 2003)

  21 Jun 2003; jje <jje@gentoo.org> speex-1.0.1.ebuild:
  Version bump, fixes bug in wideband encoding which makes 1.0 files
  play at lower quality on 1.0.1 decoders.
  
  Submitted by: Roland McIntosh <gentoo@rgm.nu>

  12 Jun 2003; <msterret@gentoo.org> speex-1.0.ebuild, speex-1.0_beta3.ebuild:
  fix Header

*speex-1.0 (28 Mar 2003)

  05 Apr 2003; Jason Wever <weeve@gentoo.org> speex-1.0.ebuild:
  Added ~sparc to keywords.

  28 Mar 2003; Michael Imhof <tantive@gentoo.org> speex-1.0.ebuild :
  User submission from Andy Dustman <andy-gentoo.54e552@dustman.net>.
  Masked it until someone confirms it works as it should.
  Should close #18396.

*speex-1.0_beta3 (12 Nov 2002)

  15 nov 2002; Nick Hadaway <raker@gentoo.org> speex-1.0_beta3.ebuild :
  Added ppc

  12 Nov 2002; Matt Keadle <mkeadle@gentoo.org> speex-1.0_beta3.ebuild
  files/digest-speex-1.0_beta3

  The most obvious change is going from 'Speex' to 'speex'. This is heading to
  portage unmasked as there are a few things wanting to depend on it. Has been
  very stable on four test machines here.

  This is an extention of the ChangeLog for 'Speex', so that its previous
  records can still be available.

*Speex-1.0_beta2-r1 (6 Nov 2002)

  6 Nov 2002; Matt Keadle <mkeadle@gentoo.org> Speex-1.0_beta2-r1.ebuild files/digest-Speex-1.0_beta2-r1 :

  manual.pdf now goes into /usr/share/doc/Speex and gcc issues seem to be resolved.

*Speex-1.0_beta2 (29 Oct 2002) Bart Verwilst <verwilst@gentoo.org>

